# Page Builder Extensions

This project will extend the existing builder with a new programmable section editor that exposes primitives, variants, configuration, and compile preview.

- Section editor must provide users with the available UI primitives and variants as first-class choices, not as hard-coded page components.
- Derived/custom section editors must let users choose a registered component to render each datasource row.
- Each section should expose a schema-driven config surface for block-specific props, layout, and style options.
- Component picker choices must include primitive elements such as `div`, text, button, checkbox, image/media, link, icon/status badge, card surfaces, and compound layouts made from those primitives.
- Top-level repeatable components must document which bind points can receive row data and which value shapes they accept.
- The builder will support `UI` and `Code` tabs, plus an `Events`/`Scripts` tab when applicable.
- A shared Monaco editor will power TypeScript scripting for section-level logic, event handlers, and programmable compilation.
- The editor experience should mirror the datasource editor model, with tabbed views and compile/run validation.
- Users can configure available events and write TypeScript handlers for those events in the page builder.
- Section compilation should be referenceable from the editor: the code tab can compile into a section definition, while the UI tab edits schema-driven props.
- Keep the code editor shared across the page builder so datasource scripts, custom section code, and event scripts use the same Monaco/TypeScript environment.
- Where possible, preserve the current page builder’s live save semantics while allowing code compilation errors to be surfaced before persist.

