# Phased Implementation

Phase 1 — Align with current Skaia page model

- Keep existing `pages` table and `Content` JSON storage.
- Treat page section/block JSON and current section block types as the canonical schema.
- Ensure page builder uses current block components and section metadata.

Phase 2 — Add explicit section metadata

- Introduce a section registry API for allowed block types and config schema.
- Add backend validation for supported `section_type`s and datasource references.
- Wire builder dropdowns to the registry metadata.

Phase 3 — Enforce integration primitives

- Make `data_sources`, `derived_section`, and `custom_section` first-class builder primitives.
- Ensure builder can only save those blocks when referenced backends exist.
- Validate custom-section templates and datasource execution metadata.

Phase 4 — Add component registry and bind-point contracts

- Introduce canonical component definitions for supported primitive and compound components.
- Document bind points, value kinds, style targets, repeatability, and validation schemas.
- Add backend validation for selected component type, bind mappings, required bind points, and style override safety.
- Add registry API endpoints for component metadata and, later, custom component inspection.

Phase 5 — Open derived/custom sections to registered primitive components

- Let `derived_section` choose a row component from the component registry instead of assuming one fixed card layout.
- Let `custom_section` choose or embed a saved custom component definition with explicit bind points.
- Add builder UI for mapping datasource columns/object paths/literal values to component bind points.
- Support media, link, text/rich text, boolean, object, and array bindings with clear validation feedback.
- Replicate the selected component per datasource row using `row_key_column`, `bindings`, `row_overrides`, and `style_overrides`.

Phase 6 — Convert routes to dynamic page rendering

- Render landing page and custom pages fully from stored page content.
- Replace hardcoded route UI with registry-driven page blocks where feasible.
- Keep comments/likes and ownership flows intact.

Phase 7 — Add versioning and migration

- Add version metadata for block and component schema.
- Support fallback/render path for legacy saved section payloads.
- Migrate legacy page section data into the new registry-driven shape.

---

# Key Constraints

- Backend is authoritative for page content and block schema.
- Frontend may not persist unknown `section_type`s or unsupported integration references.
- All saved page content must be renderable from stored JSON and supported block definitions.
- Integration-specific blocks must be validated against Skaia's datasource/custom-section API surface.

---

# Final Note

This plan is Skaia-specific: it builds on the current page builder, section block model, and datasource/custom-section integration. The primary work is not to invent a generic registry from scratch, but to tighten schema validation, centralize section metadata, and make custom page content the authoritative source for dynamic UI.
